description: From Middle English wodeland, wodelond, from Old English wuduland (“woodland; forestland; forest”), equivalent to wood +‎ land. Compare West Frisian wâldlân, Dutch bosland, German Waldland, Icelandic skóglendi.

adjectives.description: woodland (comparative more woodland, superlative most woodland)

entries.meaning: Of a creature or object: growing, living, or existing in a woodland.
examples: The woodland creatures ran from the fire.

entries.meaning: (obsolete) Having the character of a woodland.
